<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_ui_action` row that
    declares the `Resolve` form button on the `x_casemgmt_case` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    The concrete scope identifier `x_casemgmt` is used consistently throughout
    this repository per ../docs/state-machine.md: "ServiceNow Update Set imports
    use a standard XML parser, so the scope id must be concrete in every record
    before the Update Set is exported." All sibling XML records in this Update
    Set use `x_casemgmt` byte-for-byte; this UI Action follows the same
    convention. The AAP Section 0.7.2 placeholder `x_[scope]_` is a TEMPLATE
    that resolves to `x_casemgmt_` at materialization time.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, row 5):
        From          To             Required condition / behavior
        In Progress   Resolved       All linked x_casemgmt_case_task records
                                     have status = Closed
                                     Failure: Surface "All tasks must be closed
                                     before resolving this case."

    This UI Action is the user-facing ENTRY POINT for the In Progress -> Resolved
    transition - the FIFTH forward transition in the case state-machine
    (Draft -> Open -> In Progress -> [Pending <-> In Progress] -> Resolved -> Closed).
    It surfaces a "Resolve" button on the case form whenever the case is currently
    in `In Progress` status AND the current user is authorized (case_manager OR
    assigned case_agent). Clicking the button advances the case to Resolved
    status, provided that the transition guard `canTransitionToResolved` from
    the central Script Include
    ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml passes (i.e., zero
    child x_casemgmt_case_task records have status != 'Closed'). Failure surfaces
    the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 error message
    "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
    on the form via gs.addErrorMessage.

    THE TASK-CLOSURE GUARD - WHY RESOLVE IS THE SEMANTIC CRUX OF THE STATE MACHINE:

        The In Progress -> Resolved transition is the most semantically loaded
        transition in the entire case lifecycle. It encodes the business rule
        that a case cannot be considered "done" until all of its child work
        items are themselves done. The rule is enforced by querying the
        x_casemgmt_case_task table for child rows whose `case` reference
        points at the current case AND whose `status` is not 'Closed' - if
        any such row exists, the transition is blocked.

        The check is delegated to the central Script Include's
        canTransitionToResolved(caseGr) method, which itself delegates to
        getOpenTaskCountForCase(caseSysId) - a GlideAggregate-based COUNT(*)
        query for efficiency (avoids loading task rows). The boolean predicate
        (count > 0) and the verbatim error message are computed inside the
        Script Include so the validator's API stays uniform with the other
        canTransitionTo* methods.

        Per AAP Section 0.7.2 Rule 6 ("Delegate to Script Include - DO NOT
        inline GlideRecord('x_casemgmt_case_task') query directly"), the UI
        Action does NOT inline the open-task count query. The Script Include
        is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for both the count logic and the
        verbatim error message text, shared with:
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml (the Flow
            Designer subflow that fires on the OnUpdate trigger of the two
            parent state-machine flows; covers non-form transition paths
            like Table API and scripted REST)
          - Any future scripted REST endpoint or scheduled job that performs
            In Progress -> Resolved transitions

        Centralizing the guard in the Script Include guarantees that the
        verbatim error message text "All tasks must be closed before resolving
        this case." (AAP Section 0.7.4) is identical across all callers (no
        drift between this UI Action's surfaced message and the flow's
        surfaced message), and future rule changes only need to be made in
        one place.

    SERVER-SIDE-ONLY PATTERN (matches sibling case_open.xml, case_resume.xml,
    case_start_progress.xml; contrasts with case_set_pending.xml):

        Unlike the Set Pending UI Action which uses a hybrid client+server
        pattern (it must collect the `pending_reason` value via prompt() on
        the client before submitting), this Resolve UI Action runs ENTIRELY
        on the server. There is no input to collect - the transition has no
        required parameters beyond the existing child task rows on the case.
        The single click invokes the server script directly via the platform's
        standard form-button verb pipeline, with no <onclick> JavaScript and
        no client-side function definition.

        Phase 1 - User clicks the "Resolve" button.
        Phase 2 - The platform evaluates the visibility <condition> on the
                  server when the form was rendered; the button is shown
                  only if the condition was true (status==In Progress AND
                  user is case_manager OR assigned case_agent).
        Phase 3 - The platform invokes the form-submit verb derived from
                  this UI Action's sys_name (`sysverb_x_casemgmt_case_resolve`).
        Phase 4 - The platform binds `current` (the case GlideRecord),
                  `gs` (GlideSystem), `action` (UI Action helper), and
                  evaluates the <script> body in a server sandbox.
        Phase 5 - The script performs four layers of defense-in-depth
                  validation (role, status, "Assigned only" for agents,
                  transition guard) before executing the transition.
        Phase 6 - The script sets current.status = 'Resolved' and calls
                  current.update() ONCE to persist the change.
        Phase 7 - The script calls action.setRedirectURL(current) to
                  refresh the form so the operator sees the updated status.

        The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
        before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
          - x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml (skipped because previous
            status was In Progress, not Closed)
          - x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml (skipped because
            current status is Resolved, not Draft)
          - x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml (passes if
            assigned_agent is still a member of assigned_group; in normal
            workflow this should already be true when the case reached
            In Progress)
          - x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml (skipped
            because target status is Resolved, not In Progress; pending_reason
            should already be empty since In Progress has no pending_reason)
          - x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml (skipped because target status
            is Resolved, not Closed; the closed_date side-effect fires on
            the SUBSEQUENT Resolved -> Closed transition via case_close.xml)

        The two Flow Designer flows (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
        complaint_state_machine.xml) also fire on this update via their
        OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, calling the
        validate_resolved_transition subflow which itself delegates to
        x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToResolved() - the
        SAME helper this UI Action calls. Together they form a defense-in-depth
        guard pair: the UI Action blocks the transition at the form level
        (better UX - user sees the error message immediately), and the flow
        blocks it at the workflow level (catches Table API and other non-form
        paths).

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only context, NOT byte-for-byte
    ported per AAP Section 0.2.1):

        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
        line 79-114 - the central ArkCase case state-machine service. Its
        `changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState, ipAddress)` method:

            1) Loads the CaseFile by ID (line 85)
            2) Returns early if status unchanged (lines 88-91) - mirrored
               here by the defense-in-depth check `current.status != 'In
               Progress'` (we do NOT redundantly re-check whether the new
               state equals the old state, because the visibility <condition>
               already gates the button on `current.status == 'In Progress'`,
               and our only target newState is 'Resolved' so by definition
               we are changing state)
            3) Sets the new status (line 95: retval.setStatus(newState)) -
               mirrored here by `current.status = 'Resolved'`
            4) For "CLOSED" status, sets close timestamp (lines 97-100) -
               irrelevant for this UI Action which targets Resolved (not
               Closed); the closed_date stamp fires later on the Resolved
               -> Closed transition via the case_close.xml UI Action
            5) Saves the entity (line 102: getDao().save(retval)) -
               mirrored here by `current.update()`
            6) Raises an event for downstream listeners (line 106) -
               INTENTIONALLY OMITTED per the email-disabled constraint
               (AAP Section 0.7.2). ArkCase's raiseEvent() call would have
               triggered downstream notification listeners; the ServiceNow
               POC has no equivalent gs.eventQueue() call because email is
               disabled on the PDI and no other in-scope listeners need
               the event.

        That single Java method covered EVERY transition by string-matching
        the `newState` parameter. The ServiceNow target instead splits
        per-transition logic across:
          - This UI Action (In Progress -> Resolved, the resolve edge)
          - Sibling UI Actions for every other transition
          - The central Script Include CaseTransitionValidator (single
            source of truth for transition guards, called from this UI
            Action AND from the Flow Designer subflow
            validate_resolved_transition.xml)
          - The two parent state-machine flows (which also trigger on
            this status change via their OnUpdate filters)

        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/CaseFileTasksService.java -
        the source-side interface for "fetch tasks for this case". ArkCase
        used this interface (and its Solr-backed implementation,
        CaseFileTasksServiceImpl) to retrieve task lists for display.
        The ServiceNow target's task-aggregation use case is narrower:
        we only need to know whether ANY child task is open, not retrieve
        the full list. The Script Include's getOpenTaskCountForCase
        substitutes a GlideAggregate COUNT(*) for ArkCase's Solr query,
        eliminating the need for a search engine entirely (Solr is out
        of POC scope per AAP Section 0.3.2).

    BUTTON VISIBILITY CONDITION (the <condition> field):

        The button is shown when ALL of the following are true:
          1) current.status == 'In Progress'  (the source state of the
             In Progress -> Resolved transition)
          2) The current user holds either:
             a) the x_casemgmt_case_manager role (managers see the button
                on EVERY In Progress case, regardless of assignment), OR
             b) the x_casemgmt_case_agent role AND the case is "Assigned
                only" to them, where "Assigned only" is encoded as:
                current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() OR
                gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())
                per AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim: "Assigned only = cases
                where assigned_agent = current user OR assigned_group
                contains current user".

        The visibility check runs server-side (the <condition> field is
        evaluated by the platform when rendering the form). The
        defense-in-depth check inside the <script> body re-validates the
        same conditions on the server when the button is clicked, providing
        two layers of validation that protect against:
          - Form-tampering attacks where the user edits hidden form fields
            to attempt the transition from a non-In-Progress state
          - Race conditions where the user opens the form, the case
            transitions out of In Progress in another browser tab, then the
            user clicks Resolve in the original tab
          - Role escalation attempts where a viewer somehow gains access
            to the form

        The .toString() coercion on assigned_group resolves the GlideElement
        reference to its sys_id string, which is what gs.getUser().isMemberOf()
        expects. The defensive null-check (current.assigned_group ? ...) in
        the script body protects against the edge case where assigned_group
        is empty even though the case is in In Progress (shouldn't happen if
        the Draft -> Open transition was properly enforced, but defense in
        depth handles edge cases like direct Table API edits that bypassed
        canTransitionToOpen).

    DELIBERATE OMISSION FROM VISIBILITY CONDITION (open-task check):

        The visibility <condition> deliberately does NOT include the
        open-task count check (i.e., it does NOT pre-query
        x_casemgmt_case_task to determine whether any child tasks are
        open). This is intentional defense-in-depth UX:

          - If the button were hidden whenever any task were open, the
            user would have NO indication of how to advance the case.
            They would see an In Progress case with no Resolve button
            and be stuck guessing what to do.

          - With the button always visible on In Progress cases (subject
            only to the role/assignment check), the user can click it
            and immediately receive the explicit blocking error
            "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
            This tells them exactly what to do: close all child tasks,
            then retry.

          - Pre-querying child task counts in EVERY form rendering would
            add an N+1 query overhead to every case form load (one extra
            COUNT query per row in any list rendering). Deferring the
            check to click-time means the query runs only when the user
            actually attempts the transition.

        This matches the AAP Section 0.5.5 row 5 "Surface 'All tasks must
        be closed before resolving this case.'" pattern - the user gets
        explicit feedback rather than a silently hidden control. The same
        UX philosophy applies to all sibling transition UI Actions in this
        folder.

    DELEGATION TO SCRIPT INCLUDE (single source of truth):

        The transition-guard logic lives EXCLUSIVELY in
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml's
        canTransitionToResolved(caseGr) method, which:

          - Takes the case GlideRecord as a parameter
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' }
            if caseGr is null/undefined
          - Returns { ok: false, error: 'All tasks must be closed before
            resolving this case.' } if any child x_casemgmt_case_task
            has status != 'Closed' (the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4
            blocking-error message)
          - Returns { ok: true } if the transition is permitted

        Internally the Script Include calls getOpenTaskCountForCase(caseSysId),
        which uses GlideAggregate('x_casemgmt_case_task') with
        addQuery('case', caseSysId), addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed'),
        and addAggregate('COUNT'). This is more efficient than
        GlideRecord.getRowCount() because it does not load row data.

        The same helper is invoked by:
          - This UI Action (the form-button entry point)
          - ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml (the Flow
            Designer subflow that runs the SAME guard via the parent
            state-machine flows' OnUpdate trigger; covers non-form transition
            paths like Table API and scripted REST)
          - Any future scripted REST endpoint or scheduled job that
            performs In Progress -> Resolved transitions

        Centralizing the guard in the Script Include guarantees:
          - The verbatim error message text "All tasks must be closed
            before resolving this case." (AAP Section 0.7.4) is identical
            across all callers (no drift between the UI Action's surfaced
            message and the flow's surfaced message)
          - Future rule changes (e.g., adding a second precondition like
            "must have at least one party associated") only need to be made
            in one place
          - The single source of truth aligns with AAP Section 0.4.3
            "Shared transition-guard Script Include" design pattern

        The UI Action consumes the helper's { ok, error } contract:
            var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
            var result   = validator.canTransitionToResolved(current);
            if (!result.ok) {
                gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
                action.setRedirectURL(current);
                return;
            }
        It does NOT inline the GlideAggregate query. The Rule 6 in the
        agent prompt ("Delegate to Script Include - DO NOT inline a
        GlideRecord('x_casemgmt_case_task') query directly in this UI
        Action") is honored.

    CHOICE-VALUE BYTE-FOR-BYTE REQUIREMENTS (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim):

        The two case-status labels referenced in this UI Action are:

            'In Progress'  (11 chars, two words separated by a literal SPACE,
                            Title Case - NOT 'In_Progress', NOT 'InProgress',
                            NOT 'IN PROGRESS', NOT 'in progress')
            'Resolved'     (8 chars, single word, Title Case)

        These MUST match the labels in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
        byte-for-byte. ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string
        by default (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the
        label text. Misspellings such as 'IN PROGRESS' (uppercase),
        'in progress' (lowercase), or 'In_Progress' (with underscore) would
        silently never match and the UI Action would never fire.

        Additionally, the child-task status referenced indirectly through
        the Script Include's getOpenTaskCountForCase query is 'Closed'
        (8 chars, single word, Title Case), defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml. The check
        addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed') matches against this exact label.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table>x_casemgmt_case</table>             scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>          scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>      scoped application
        - <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
          scoped roles (comma-separated; both roles see the button, but
          the visibility <condition> further filters case_agent visibility
          to assigned cases only per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix
          "Assigned only" rule)
        - script body references current.status, current.assigned_agent,
          current.assigned_group (all on the scoped table x_casemgmt_case)
          and instantiates new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator() (the
          scoped Script Include)

        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.
        Zero global ACL or role mutations.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        - <table> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <roles> resolves both roles BY NAME
          (x_casemgmt_case_manager, x_casemgmt_case_agent)
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          GlideRecord and `gs.getUser()` / `gs.getUserID()` calls and
          delegates to the named Script Include via
          new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator().
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The .toString() coercion on current.assigned_group resolves a
          RUNTIME GlideElement reference to its sys_id string, NOT a
          hardcoded literal. The platform method gs.getUser().isMemberOf()
          accepts either a sys_id or a group name; passing the runtime
          field value is the canonical pattern.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_resolve"), which is
          permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies
          to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not to a
          record's own primary key.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any email
        notification event since email is disabled on the PDI. This UI
        Action contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email() calls,
        and zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs only the
        status update and an action.setRedirectURL refresh.

    NO PII CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):

        The script body, code comments, description text, hint text, and
        all error messages contain zero real names, real email addresses,
        real phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any other
        personally identifiable information. The UI Action operates
        exclusively on synthetic case-status enumerations (In Progress,
        Resolved, Closed) and synthetic role identifiers
        (x_casemgmt_case_manager, x_casemgmt_case_agent).

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):

        This sys_ui_action record MUST be loaded AFTER:
