    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:

        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_case_resolve")
               = fcef26b5dd69234a0b4a8ea82d997b17
        32-character lowercase hex. Recomputable via:
            printf '%s' 'x_casemgmt_case_resolve' | md5sum | cut -c1-32

        Deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent re-import on a
        fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set produces the same
        sys_id, which collides on the existing record and updates it in
        place rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same convention
        used by all sibling UI Actions in this folder.

    ORDER WITHIN UI ACTION SEQUENCE:

        order=500 places Resolve as the FIFTH UI Action in the workflow
        sequence (second-to-last, before Close at order=600):
            1) Open               (order=100       - Draft -> Open)
            2) Start Progress     (order=200       - Open -> In Progress)
            3) Set Pending        (order=300       - In Progress -> Pending)
            4) Resume             (order=400       - Pending -> In Progress)
            5) Resolve            (order=500, THIS - In Progress -> Resolved)
            6) Close              (order=600       - Resolved -> Closed)

        The ordering is for UI display only - the platform renders form
        buttons in ascending order. Only one button is visible at a time
        (each visibility <condition> matches a different status), so the
        ordering does not affect runtime correctness. Resolve carries
        order=500 because it is the second-to-last transition in the
        canonical forward sequence.

    FORM_STYLE = primary:

        Resolve is the AFFIRMATIVE PENULTIMATE STEP from In Progress. The
        user is moving the case toward completion (the next-and-final step
        is Close). The button is rendered with the platform's primary visual
        style (typically a filled-color button) to draw attention. This
        contrasts with Close, which uses form_style=destructive because
        closing a case is a TERMINAL action (per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 8
        "Closed: Terminal state. No transitions permitted from Closed.").
        Resolve uses primary because the case is moving forward (resolution
        is positive progress) but is not yet truly terminal - the case can
        still be closed afterward by a manager.

    MANAGER-AND-AGENT VISIBILITY (AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix):

        Both x_casemgmt_case_manager and x_casemgmt_case_agent see the
        Resolve button. The rationale per AAP Section 0.5.6:

          - case_manager has full access (Create + Read All + Write All +
            Delete on the case table). Resolve is a Write operation. Per
            the ACL matrix, manager can write any case regardless of
            assignment.

          - case_agent has Write Assigned only access. Resolve is a Write
            operation. Per the ACL matrix and verbatim "Assigned only =
            cases where assigned_agent = current user OR assigned_group
            contains current user", agent can resolve cases they are
            assigned to OR cases assigned to a group they belong to.

          - case_viewer has only Read All access (no Write). Resolve is
            a Write operation. case_viewer is therefore excluded from
            the <roles> field.

        The visibility <condition> further filters case_agent visibility
        to assigned cases only via the OR'd sub-clauses:
            current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()
            OR
            gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())
        case_manager bypasses this filter via the "OR has manager role"
        clause at the top of the condition, so managers see the button
        on every In Progress case.

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):

        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error;
          task-closure check blocks Resolved transition". This UI Action
          is the PRIMARY user-facing trigger for the In Progress ->
          Resolved transition (per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 5). The Script
          Include's canTransitionToResolved enforces the task-closure
          check and surfaces the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 blocking-error
          message "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          if violated. The defense-in-depth role, status, and "Assigned
          only" re-checks prevent stale-form submissions from corrupting
          the state machine.

        - Gate 3 (ACLs): "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot
          write; case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager
          has full access". This UI Action's visibility <condition> and
          server-side defense-in-depth check both encode the role rules
          from AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim. case_viewer is excluded by the
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager,x_casemgmt_case_agent</roles>
          field. case_agent on an unassigned case is excluded by the
          "Assigned only" sub-condition.

        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set loads
          without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The deterministic
          sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and absence of any external
          lookups guarantee this UI Action re-imports cleanly with zero
          preview errors.

