        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 5 (In Progress -> Resolved):
    //   "All linked x_casemgmt_case_task records have status = Closed"
    //   "Surface 'All tasks must be closed before resolving this case.'"
    //   - VERBATIM blocking-error message per AAP Section 0.7.4
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.1: blocking errors must appear on the form.
    //
    // This is the SERVER-side click handler for the Resolve form button.
    // It runs in the server sandbox (no window, has current GlideRecord,
    // has gs and action) and is responsible for:
    //   1) Defense-in-depth role re-check (case_manager OR case_agent).
    //   2) Defense-in-depth status re-check (must be 'In Progress').
    //   3) Defense-in-depth "Assigned only" re-check for case_agents.
    //   4) Delegation to the central Script Include's canTransitionToResolved
    //      method, which encapsulates the "all child tasks must be Closed"
    //      guard AND the verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 error message.
    //   5) Status persistence (current.status = 'Resolved'; current.update()).
    //   6) Form refresh (action.setRedirectURL(current)).
    //
    // Each of the four guards above maps to a row in the AAP Section
    // 0.5.6 ACL matrix or the AAP Section 0.5.5 transition map:
    //   - Guard 1: Role check enforces "Only case_manager or case_agent
    //     can perform write transitions" (case_viewer is read-only per
    //     ACL matrix).
    //   - Guard 2: Status check enforces "Only In Progress -> Resolved"
    //     (no other transition can fire this handler).
    //   - Guard 3: Assigned only check enforces case_agent's assigned-only
    //     write privilege (case_manager bypasses this guard).
    //   - Guard 4: The Script Include's canTransitionToResolved check
    //     enforces "all child x_casemgmt_case_task have status = Closed"
    //     per the AAP transition map; on failure it returns the verbatim
    //     AAP Section 0.7.4 message.
    //
    // All four guards must pass before current.update() is called.
    // Any guard failure surfaces a blocking gs.addErrorMessage and
    // returns without persisting.

    // Guard 1: Role check. The user must hold case_manager OR case_agent.
    // (case_viewer is excluded by the <roles> field already, but the
    // server-side re-check protects against the rare case where a user
    // lost the role between form load and form submit, and against
    // attempts to invoke the form-submit verb directly via Table API.)
    if (!gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager') && !gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent')) {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers and assigned case agents can resolve cases.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 2: Status check. The case must currently be In Progress.
    // Re-checking on the server protects against a stale-form attack
    // where the user opens the form when status is In Progress, the
    // case transitions in another tab, then the user submits from the
    // original tab. The check uses string comparison against the
    // verbatim Title Case 'In Progress' label (note the literal SPACE
    // between 'In' and 'Progress') per AAP Section 0.5.7.
    if (current.status != 'In Progress') {
        gs.addErrorMessage('Only In Progress cases can be resolved.');
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // Guard 3: Assigned only check for case_agents. case_managers
    // bypass this guard (they can resolve any case). For case_agents,
    // the case must be assigned to them directly OR they must be a
    // member of the assigned_group, per AAP Section 0.5.6 verbatim:
    // "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
    // assigned_group contains current user".
    //
    // The .toString() coercion on assigned_group resolves the GlideElement
    // reference to its sys_id string, which is what gs.getUser().isMemberOf()
    // expects. Without the coercion, the GlideElement-vs-string comparison
    // can behave inconsistently across releases. The defensive ternary
    // null-check (assigned_group ? ... : '') protects against the edge
    // case where assigned_group is empty even though the case is in In
    // Progress (shouldn't happen if the Draft -> Open transition was
    // properly enforced, but defense in depth handles edge cases like
    // direct Table API edits that bypassed canTransitionToOpen).
    if (gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_agent') && !gs.getUser().hasRole('x_casemgmt_case_manager')) {
        var groupIdForAuth = current.assigned_group ? current.assigned_group.toString() : '';
        var isAssigned = (current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID()) ||
                         (groupIdForAuth && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupIdForAuth));
        if (!isAssigned) {
            gs.addErrorMessage('Only case managers and assigned case agents can resolve cases.');
            action.setRedirectURL(current);
            return;
        }
    }

    // Guard 4: Transition guard. Delegate the all-tasks-closed check
    // to the central Script Include - the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for
    // both the count logic AND the verbatim error message text, shared
    // with the Flow Designer subflow ../flows/sub_flows/validate_
    // resolved_transition.xml. Centralizing the guard guarantees that:
    //   - The verbatim AAP Section 0.7.4 error message "All tasks must
    //     be closed before resolving this case." is identical across
    //     all callers (no drift between this UI Action's surfaced
    //     message and the flow's surfaced message).
    //   - Future rule changes (e.g., adding a second precondition like
    //     "must have at least one party associated") only need to be
    //     made in the Script Include.
    //   - The GlideAggregate query against x_casemgmt_case_task lives
    //     in only one place (the Script Include's getOpenTaskCountForCase
    //     helper), avoiding duplication and ensuring consistent query
    //     semantics.
    //
    // The Script Include's canTransitionToResolved(caseGr) method
    // returns:
    //   { ok: true } when zero open child tasks remain, OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'All tasks must be closed before resolving
    //     this case.' } when at least one child task has status != Closed
    //     (the VERBATIM AAP Section 0.7.4 message), OR
    //   { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' } when caseGr is
    //     null/undefined (defensive guard against unexpected input).
    //
    // The result.error string is surfaced verbatim via gs.addErrorMessage,
    // NOT replaced with a hardcoded UI-Action-local message. This honors
    // the agent prompt's Rule 5 ("VERBATIM Error Message - The error
    // message MUST come from the Script Include's result.error field -
    // NOT inlined as a hardcoded string in this UI Action") and Rule 6
    // ("Delegate to Script Include - DO NOT inline a GlideRecord query
    // here").
    var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
    var result = validator.canTransitionToResolved(current);
    if (!result.ok) {
        gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
        action.setRedirectURL(current);
        return;
    }

    // All four guards passed. Perform the In Progress -> Resolved
    // transition. The status assignment uses the verbatim Title Case
    // 'Resolved' label per AAP Section 0.5.7 and the sibling choice
    // file ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml.
    //
    // The single current.update() call triggers the platform's full
    // before-update Business Rule pipeline, including:
    //   - block_terminal_closed (no-op, previous status was In Progress
    //     not Closed)
    //   - block_draft_backtransition (no-op, target is Resolved not Draft)
    //   - validate_assigned_agent_membership (passes if assigned_agent
    //     is still a member of assigned_group; in normal workflow this
    //     should already be true when the case reached In Progress)
    //   - clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress (no-op, target is Resolved
    //     not In Progress; pending_reason should already be empty)
    //   - set_closed_date (no-op, target is Resolved not Closed; the
    //     closed_date stamp fires on the SUBSEQUENT Resolved -> Closed
    //     transition via case_close.xml)
    //
    // The two parent state-machine flows (general_inquiry_state_machine
    // and complaint_state_machine) ALSO fire on this update via their
    // OnUpdate triggers filtered on `status` change, calling the
    // validate_resolved_transition subflow which itself delegates to
    // x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToResolved() -
    // the SAME helper this UI Action just called. Belt-and-suspenders
    // defense in depth.
    current.status = 'Resolved';
    current.update();

    // Refresh the form to show the new status. The standard ServiceNow
    // UI-Action pattern is to call action.setRedirectURL(current) which
    // navigates the browser to the same record's form view, picking up
    // the new status and any side-effect field changes (e.g., audit
    // timestamps updated by the platform's standard sys_* pipeline).
    action.setRedirectURL(current);
})();]]></script>
